The Facebook signup story

Think about the day you made your Facebook account.

You typed your name and password, clicked "Sign Up", and one thing happened that you asked for: your account got made.

But behind the scenes, a bunch of stuff also happened on its own:

- 📧 a welcome email landed in your inbox
- 👤 an empty profile got created for you
- 🔔 maybe a "verify your email" message popped up

You didn't ask for those. You clicked one button. The rest just… happened automatically.

That "automatically happened" part — that's a signal. ✨

In plain words

A signal is just this idea:

▎ "When THIS happens, automatically do THAT."

That's the whole thing.

- When a new account is made → automatically send a welcome email.
- When a new account is made → automatically create a profile.

The person signing up doesn't do these. The system has a standing rule: "any time someone signs up, do these extra things by myself."

Our version

In our app, we want the exact same kind of rule:

▎ "When a new user is made → automatically create their OTPCode (their secret)."

Just like Facebook auto-makes your profile, we auto-make the user's secret. We don't want to do it by hand every time. We set the rule once, and Django does it forever.

New user signs up  →  (automatically)  →  their OTPCode gets created

That's it. That's a signal. 🎯

